\par <#/>Environmental laws in Kenya are not gender specific in that at their enactment they were geared towards both men and women. <#/>These laws are, however, mainly concerned with those areas where women's participation is the greatest, for example agricul
t
ure, forestry, human settlement and water. <#/>It is also clear that despite the fact of gender neutrality of the law, women's experiences do not seem to have been considered in the enactment of these laws. <#/>Women have continued to be ignored, despite 
the role they play in environmental conservation.
\par <#/>Women in Kenya play a key role in agricultural production and have also contributed towards the development of that area. <#/>This is also the position in any other African countries. <#/>During the colo
nial era, women played important roles both directly and indirectly in agricultural production; however, the policy makers marginalized women's agricultural work and emphasized male wage labour on large agricultural farms. <#/>Thus women modified their ec
o
nomic activities and planted crops for subsistence. <#/>Introduction of agricultural technology and better farming techniques served the large farms, leaving the women farmers to apply their out-dated methods and techniques. <#/>Laws and policies on land 
o
wnership and access to credit also played their role in further marginalizing women, who did not own the land they tilled or have access to credit facilities for purpose of loans. <#/>As a result, in most African countries the post-colonial era introduced
 modern technologies, fertilizers and credit services for plantation agriculture, ignoring subsistence agriculture.
\par <#/>Other than participation in agricultural production, women are also engaged in gathering wood for fuel purposes and fetching water for household use. <#/>It is the same women who are household managers and bearers and care-takers of children.
\par <#/>Bearing in mind the role that women play in agricultural production, energy and water consumption and reproduction, one can clearly see that women
 have a direct impact on the environment, depending on their needs. <#/>Thus, in agriculture they have an impact on land either through crop farming or livestock keeping. <#/>In gathering wood, they have an impact on the forests; in using water from the l
a
kes and rivers, they have an impact on the available water resources. <#/>Their own health will play a role in determining the health of the children they bear. <#/>All this women's work has for very long gone unrecognized despite its contribution towards
 development.
\par <#/>Women have for a long time contributed towards environmental destruction in their day to day activities. <#/>This has gone unrecognized because women's work has continued to be ignored. <#/>If sustainable development through sound environm
ental management is to be achieved, there is need to give utmost consideration to the experiences of those persons directly concerned with the environment in their day to day activities. <#/>Thus when it comes, to good land management the experiences of w
omen need consideration. <#/>There is therefore a need for legislators and policy makers to ask themselves <foreign/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 inter }{\fs24\lang2057 <foreign/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 alia }{\v\fs24\lang2057 
why women continue to destroy the environment, or why they are ignorant of environmental management techniques.
